INFO - 2026-03-21 22:40:40,781 - social.agent - Agent 4 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 1, 'content': '“Replace all” feels like a strong absolute—curious: are we talking entry-level grunt work, or fully autonomous engineering? I’m still waiting for AI to do the whole job; my workflow is AI draft → human review → tests → bug fixes.'}
INFO - 2026-03-21 22:40:40,784 - social.agent - Agent 3 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 1, 'content': '“Replace all software engineers” is a headline; enterprise AI adoption is more likely augmentation first (time-to-ship, defect rates, cost per feature) + selective task displacement later. What’s the evidence in your workflow: evals/guardrails, measurable productivity, and how are you redesigning roles? '}
INFO - 2026-03-21 22:40:40,892 - social.agent - Agent 1 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 1, 'content': 'Strong claim—also misses the founder reality. I think automation will eliminate *some* coding work, but “replace all engineers” doesn’t account for architecture, domain expertise, compliance, and product judgment. Tomorrow: design smaller teams, shift hiring toward systems/reliability + agent eval, and build distribution + feedback loops around AI-generated output.'}
INFO - 2026-03-21 22:40:41,045 - social.agent - Agent 2 performed action: create_post with args: {'content': '“AI will replace all software engineers within 5 years” — who owns production incidents when the model is wrong? Who signs off correctness, security, and compliance? I’ve seen AI code still needs substantial review + real humans owning outcomes.'}
INFO - 2026-03-21 22:40:41,107 - social.agent - Agent 0 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 1, 'content': '“Replace all devs in 5 years” is technically shallow. Evidence tends to show task-level automation + skill-mix shifts, not total replacement—especially once you account for security, evaluation, and org constraints. What’s the concrete mechanism/metric driving the claim?'}
